3
00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:11.690
So we already covered part of this.

4
00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:14.480
When you're sitting, plant your feet firmly on the ground.

5
00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:21.500
I have your torso and the rest of your body facing the camera and your shoulders up and out slightly

6
00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:23.020
to project confidence.

7
00:00:23.030 --> 00:00:30.380
You do not want to round your shoulders out or slouch them or have your head disappear into your neck

8
00:00:30.380 --> 00:00:38.300
like this, because that shows a lack of confidence and you want to project yourself as the candidate

9
00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:42.320
that that can solve the problem that the interviewers have.

10
00:00:42.350 --> 00:00:44.630
Now, what happens if you're standing?

11
00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:51.170
Then you want to make sure that your toes are pointing towards the interviewer and especially when you

12
00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:51.860
greet them.

13
00:00:53.010 --> 00:01:01.230
This is vital because when your toes are pointing to in any other direction, then you will not be entirely

14
00:01:01.230 --> 00:01:01.980
invested.

15
00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:10.890
What it means is during the evolution of humans, the feet and the legs have been the most reliable

16
00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:15.330
partners for us to run away or to face danger.

17
00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:24.710
And in order to do that, the feet have just like other extremities.

18
00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:30.800
When you're faced in an uncomfortable situation, then all the blood flows to your extremities, your

19
00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:34.340
fingertips, your feet, your toes, things like that.

20
00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:41.330
So when you're not comfortable and you don't want to be in an interview, you don't want to be in that

21
00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:48.620
situation, then the first thing, the most reliable indicator of that would be your toes, and they

22
00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:50.030
would point towards the exit.

23
00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:56.330
Now if you're pointing towards the exit, then that immediately tells me, for example, that you don't

24
00:01:56.330 --> 00:02:01.260
want to be part of that conversation, and that would be a red flag.

25
00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:03.260
We want to avoid red flags here.

26
00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:04.640
Face the interviewer.

27
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.610
What if you have multiple interviewers?

28
00:02:07.610 --> 00:02:14.930
You always know that one person is the leader of that group and the main interviewer.

29
00:02:14.930 --> 00:02:23.330
They may not be the topmost boss, but they will be the ones that they will be the person that takes

30
00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:28.280
charge and wants to interview you and face them.

31
00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:34.790
And if you don't know who that person is, then face everyone else equally and try to face the person

32
00:02:34.790 --> 00:02:35.570
in the middle.

33
00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:41.690
And it's okay to turn your torso when you're talking to different people like this.

34
00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:47.780
But you don't need to turn your entire body, your your toes don't need to shift from one person to

35
00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:55.910
another every time you answer a question put forth by a different interviewer, so be stable.

36
00:02:56.390 --> 00:03:03.920
And another piece of advice would be your physical stability in the stability of your structure will

37
00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:07.070
determine how confident your responses are as well.

38
00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:15.290
So don't stand don't lean too far back or to the sides, because if you're not stable enough, then

39
00:03:15.290 --> 00:03:20.810
your responses will be will not be concrete either.

40
00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:23.610
So that said.

41
00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:29.880
You also want to lean slightly forward instead of backward.

42
